1
00:00:01,675 --> 00:00:03,217
[soft instrumental music plays]

2
00:00:27,825 --> 00:00:29,533
[thunder crashes]

3
00:00:30,491 --> 00:00:32,158
[rousing music plays]

4
00:00:52,366 --> 00:00:54,158
[music fades out]

5
00:00:54,241 --> 00:00:58,241
-[phone beeping]
-[soft thunder rumbles]

6
00:00:58,825 --> 00:01:00,033
[man groans]

7
00:01:00,116 --> 00:01:00,991
[gunshot]

8
00:01:01,866 --> 00:01:04,575
[woman] There's a group of men
called The Firm.

9
00:01:05,616 --> 00:01:06,700
[door rattling]

10
00:01:06,783 --> 00:01:09,991
They've been running things
for a long, long time.

11
00:01:11,783 --> 00:01:14,575
And when they need someone
to clean up their mess...

12
00:01:14,658 --> 00:01:17,283
-[insistent banging at door]
-...they send me.

13
00:01:17,366 --> 00:01:19,575
[ominous music]

14
00:01:19,658 --> 00:01:20,991
[banging continues]

15
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:24,366
[stroke of a gong]

16
00:01:25,658 --> 00:01:27,700
[rousing music plays]

17
00:01:52,616 --> 00:01:54,075
[music fades out]

18
00:01:54,158 --> 00:01:56,325
[woman on TV] Go get your helmet.
Let's go to the store.

19
00:01:56,408 --> 00:01:59,866
-[character squeaks in protest]
-You look so cute, Nit.

20
00:02:01,033 --> 00:02:02,950
[voices argue on TV]

21
00:02:03,033 --> 00:02:04,825
[phone rings]

22
00:02:11,991 --> 00:02:13,116
[Sam sighs]

23
00:02:15,116 --> 00:02:17,616
-[man on speakerphone] Sam.
-Nathan.

24
00:02:18,741 --> 00:02:22,075
-[Nathan] Where are you?
-At home. Sewing.

25
00:02:23,116 --> 00:02:24,575
Meet me at the diner.

26
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:28,241
Why?

27
00:02:29,491 --> 00:02:31,116
How much trouble am I in?

28
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:34,491
["You'll Never Know"
by Bobby Darin plays]

29
00:02:34,575 --> 00:02:35,866
[service bell dings]

30
00:02:35,950 --> 00:02:38,283
[song continues
over diner sound system]

31
00:02:38,366 --> 00:02:40,658
An extra scoop
for my favourite client.

32
00:02:40,741 --> 00:02:41,908
Thanks, Rose.

33
00:02:45,283 --> 00:02:47,200
[ominous musical sting]

34
00:02:47,283 --> 00:02:49,866
["Half a Photograph" by
Kay Starr plays in background]

35
00:02:52,450 --> 00:02:55,200
I put in an extra scoop
for my favourite client.

36
00:02:55,283 --> 00:02:58,408
-Thanks, Rose,
-I'm sure she won't be long.

37
00:02:59,575 --> 00:03:01,783
You clearly don't know
my mother very well.

38
00:03:06,700 --> 00:03:09,450
-[thunder rumbles]
-[slow suspenseful music]

39
00:03:16,033 --> 00:03:17,325
Hey, stranger.

40
00:03:17,408 --> 00:03:19,991
-Can I lighten your load?
-Not carrying today, Rose.

41
00:03:20,075 --> 00:03:23,241
There's a first time
for everything. She's over there.

42
00:03:23,783 --> 00:03:25,991
Thanks for keeping an eye
on her.

43
00:03:26,075 --> 00:03:28,658
[rousing instrumental music]

44
00:03:48,116 --> 00:03:50,783
-[music fades out]
-You said you'd be here in 30 minutes.

45
00:03:51,450 --> 00:03:52,700
I'm a few minutes late.

46
00:03:54,200 --> 00:03:55,533
Three hours.

47
00:04:02,158 --> 00:04:03,033
You're bleeding.

48
00:04:03,116 --> 00:04:04,283
[thunder rumbles]

49
00:04:04,366 --> 00:04:06,991
Just another day at the office.
Did you bring it?

50
00:04:08,950 --> 00:04:10,075
[Sam sighs]

51
00:04:16,366 --> 00:04:17,991
Anna May sure can pick them.

52
00:04:18,700 --> 00:04:20,741
-It's loaded.
-Good girl.

53
00:04:26,283 --> 00:04:29,075
Listen, I, um...
have to disappear for a while.

54
00:04:29,908 --> 00:04:33,033
-Then I'm coming with you.
-You can't. Not this time.

55
00:04:33,950 --> 00:04:36,575
Nathan will be here soon.
He'll take care of you when I'm gone.

56
00:04:36,658 --> 00:04:39,908
-I don't want to go with Nathan.
-I'm doing this for your own good.

57
00:04:39,991 --> 00:04:42,158
I'll stay in the library
with Anna May and the others.

58
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:43,825
It's too dangerous.

59
00:04:47,366 --> 00:04:48,783
What's going on?

60
00:04:48,866 --> 00:04:50,491
[emotional music]

61
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:53,325
It's... it's complicated.

62
00:04:53,950 --> 00:04:54,825
Tell me.

63
00:04:55,991 --> 00:04:57,200
I'm not a kid any more.

64
00:04:58,658 --> 00:04:59,700
No, you're not.

65
00:05:11,283 --> 00:05:13,241
You haven't
touched your milkshake.

66
00:05:14,116 --> 00:05:16,450
Didn't want to drink it
without you.

67
00:05:27,200 --> 00:05:29,575
[climactic music]

68
00:05:52,158 --> 00:05:53,533
[music fades out]

69
00:05:54,075 --> 00:05:55,741
How long will you be gone?

70
00:05:59,491 --> 00:06:01,366
I have to make
a quick phone call.

71
00:06:02,783 --> 00:06:03,991
Stay here.

72
00:06:14,241 --> 00:06:17,491
-[door crashes open]
-[suspenseful music]

73
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:20,783
[Rose] Evening, gentlemen.
Can I lighten your load?

74
00:06:20,866 --> 00:06:22,325
-Get lost.
-Hey.

75
00:06:25,991 --> 00:06:27,991
[suspenseful music plays]

76
00:06:44,825 --> 00:06:46,741
[ominous music plays]

77
00:06:53,450 --> 00:06:55,408
[in Russian accent]
Hello, little girl.

78
00:06:56,700 --> 00:06:58,866
Mommy says I'm not allowed
to talk to strangers.

79
00:07:00,533 --> 00:07:04,366
This "Mommy"
looks a lot like you.

80
00:07:05,908 --> 00:07:08,616
Only bigger and more stabby.

81
00:07:10,075 --> 00:07:12,533
Got my father's blood
all over her.

82
00:07:17,033 --> 00:07:18,866
I don't like you.

83
00:07:18,950 --> 00:07:20,158
[gasps mockingly]

84
00:07:27,616 --> 00:07:28,825
Enough games.

85
00:07:30,075 --> 00:07:31,366
Where is she?

86
00:07:32,616 --> 00:07:34,575
[in Russian] Go kiss a pig.

87
00:07:34,658 --> 00:07:36,283
[music intensifies]

88
00:07:38,116 --> 00:07:42,575
[in English]
Tell me where she is.

89
00:07:45,241 --> 00:07:47,908
[suspenseful music intensifies]

90
00:07:48,741 --> 00:07:50,950
-[gun cocks]
-Close your eyes, baby girl.

91
00:07:51,033 --> 00:07:52,783
-[gunshots]
-[glass smashing]

92
00:07:54,658 --> 00:07:57,658
-[gunshots continue]
-[panicked grunts and shouts]

93
00:07:57,741 --> 00:08:00,366
-[man exclaims in Russian]
-[gunshots continue]

94
00:08:01,158 --> 00:08:02,908
[high-pitched ringing]

95
00:08:03,533 --> 00:08:05,783
-[hurried steps]
-[door slams]

96
00:08:06,450 --> 00:08:09,033
["Something On Your Mind"
by Karen Dalton plays]

97
00:08:11,991 --> 00:08:12,825
Mom!

98
00:08:22,158 --> 00:08:24,325
♪ Yesterday ♪

99
00:08:25,325 --> 00:08:30,366
♪ Any way you made it
was just fine ♪

100
00:08:31,991 --> 00:08:36,283
♪ So you turn your days
into nighttime ♪

101
00:08:38,075 --> 00:08:40,741
♪ Didn't you know ♪

102
00:08:41,533 --> 00:08:46,950
♪ You can't make it
Without ever even trying ♪

103
00:08:49,158 --> 00:08:53,908
♪ And something's on your mind
Isn't it? ♪

104
00:08:57,033 --> 00:08:58,783
♪ Let these times-- ♪

105
00:08:58,866 --> 00:09:02,991
[music crescendos and fades]

106
00:09:04,158 --> 00:09:05,908
[quiet music playing in diner]

107
00:09:05,991 --> 00:09:06,866
Evening, darling.

108
00:09:06,950 --> 00:09:09,033
-Can I lighten your load?
-I'm clean.

109
00:09:09,116 --> 00:09:11,200
Regular clean or diner clean?

110
00:09:13,075 --> 00:09:14,200
[chuckles ironically]

111
00:09:15,158 --> 00:09:16,200
[sighs]

112
00:09:18,575 --> 00:09:20,616
-Forgot about this one.
-Of course, sugar.

113
00:09:20,700 --> 00:09:21,741
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

114
00:09:27,158 --> 00:09:28,866
[distant thunder rumbles]

115
00:09:29,866 --> 00:09:31,158
[Nathan whispers] Boy.

116
00:09:31,741 --> 00:09:34,741
Oh, these girls
are worse than the Stasi.

117
00:09:35,491 --> 00:09:37,116
[sighs] You hurt?

118
00:09:38,908 --> 00:09:40,700
Just another day at the office.

119
00:09:40,783 --> 00:09:42,991
Wow, you sound
just like your mother.

120
00:09:44,491 --> 00:09:45,908
I don't have a mother.

121
00:09:45,991 --> 00:09:48,575
Well, you sure have her temper.

122
00:09:49,825 --> 00:09:51,408
What the hell happened tonight?

123
00:09:51,491 --> 00:09:53,241
Bad intel.

124
00:09:53,325 --> 00:09:56,200
You said four or five idiots
with peashooters.

125
00:09:56,283 --> 00:09:57,616
Yes. And?

126
00:09:57,700 --> 00:09:59,533
[discordant tone]

127
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:02,325
[diner bell dings]

128
00:10:04,116 --> 00:10:06,116
Oh, for Christ's sake, child.

129
00:10:07,241 --> 00:10:10,116
This was supposed to be low-profile,
not a bloody massacre.

130
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:12,325
Next time,
I'll just let them shoot me.

131
00:10:12,408 --> 00:10:15,325
Next time,
just do what you're told.

132
00:10:17,116 --> 00:10:20,283
Remember who you're working for.
As long as they're happy...

133
00:10:20,366 --> 00:10:23,950
You called me here oh-so-urgently
just to remind me of that?

134
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:27,200
No.

135
00:10:28,325 --> 00:10:30,408
Your talents are needed, pronto.

136
00:10:31,783 --> 00:10:33,408
Somebody stole from us.

137
00:10:35,616 --> 00:10:37,950
Who's crazy enough
to steal from The Firm?

138
00:10:38,450 --> 00:10:40,575
Somebody who doesn't know
who we really are.

139
00:10:40,658 --> 00:10:43,491
An accountant. From the
clean side of the business.

140
00:10:44,533 --> 00:10:46,033
How much did he take?

141
00:10:46,116 --> 00:10:47,991
Enough to earn
a visit from you.

142
00:10:48,075 --> 00:10:49,283
We need that money back.

143
00:10:50,825 --> 00:10:52,408
[whispers] Good girl.

144
00:10:52,491 --> 00:10:54,825
I'll text you the address later.

145
00:10:54,908 --> 00:10:58,366
Oh, and get rid of those
stone-age firearms you carry.

146
00:10:58,450 --> 00:11:01,241
-I've had them for years.
-Find an open vendor.

147
00:11:01,325 --> 00:11:04,033
And get yourself
some clean boomsticks.

148
00:11:04,116 --> 00:11:06,825
We can't have you linked to that
war zone you left behind, can we?

149
00:11:07,741 --> 00:11:08,866
[thunder rumbles]

150
00:11:09,950 --> 00:11:12,075
[soft suspenseful music plays]

151
00:11:21,991 --> 00:11:25,575
[man] Did you know about this little
endeavour my son had on the side?

152
00:11:27,116 --> 00:11:30,075
[nephew] Sorry, Uncle.
I had no idea.

153
00:11:31,658 --> 00:11:33,033
[exasperated sigh]

154
00:11:35,700 --> 00:11:37,158
[grunts, exhales]

155
00:11:55,366 --> 00:11:56,575
Where's the shoe?

156
00:11:57,866 --> 00:11:58,991
What shoe?

157
00:11:59,075 --> 00:12:02,200
The shoe that is not currently
covering my son's left foot.

158
00:12:02,908 --> 00:12:04,991
The one that looks like
the right one.

159
00:12:05,075 --> 00:12:06,283
That fucking shoe.

160
00:12:06,866 --> 00:12:08,991
-I don't know.
-Well, find it.

161
00:12:16,658 --> 00:12:18,575
[sidekick]
Found it, Mr. McAlester.

162
00:12:39,491 --> 00:12:41,658
Nobody tells his mother
about this.

163
00:12:43,366 --> 00:12:45,825
We'll tell her
he ran off with some girl.

164
00:12:46,533 --> 00:12:47,491
I get it.

165
00:12:48,283 --> 00:12:51,533
Now, bring me the heads
of the men who killed my boy.

166
00:12:51,616 --> 00:12:53,908
-[music fades out]
-[church bells chiming]

167
00:12:58,950 --> 00:13:00,241
[sighs]

168
00:13:07,533 --> 00:13:09,616
[door slams heavily]

169
00:13:11,366 --> 00:13:13,741
[church bells continue]

170
00:13:22,741 --> 00:13:23,908
[librarian] Hmm.

171
00:13:26,241 --> 00:13:27,450
[quiet chuckle]

172
00:13:27,533 --> 00:13:29,533
[inhales deeply]

173
00:13:30,658 --> 00:13:31,575
[sharp exhale]

174
00:13:33,200 --> 00:13:34,200
Hello, dear.

175
00:13:34,700 --> 00:13:35,991
What can I do for you?

176
00:13:38,741 --> 00:13:41,241
I need to exchange
some... books.

177
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:43,450
Well, that's nice.

178
00:13:44,116 --> 00:13:46,825
Not a lot of people your age
read nowadays.

179
00:13:47,700 --> 00:13:49,616
-Do you have a card with us?
-No.

180
00:13:50,283 --> 00:13:51,366
I'd like to open one.

181
00:13:52,116 --> 00:13:53,575
Wonderful.

182
00:13:53,658 --> 00:13:56,075
What kind of... books
are you interested in?

183
00:13:57,158 --> 00:13:58,408
Mostly smaller ones.

184
00:13:59,283 --> 00:14:00,158
A few heavies.

185
00:14:00,908 --> 00:14:02,575
Well, you won't find them there.

186
00:14:02,658 --> 00:14:04,575
Those are our
children's sections.

187
00:14:04,658 --> 00:14:05,783
The Enchanted Forest...

188
00:14:07,241 --> 00:14:09,158
and The Never-Ending Ocean.

189
00:14:11,075 --> 00:14:12,408
They sound like fun.

190
00:14:14,033 --> 00:14:15,450
[soft music plays]

191
00:14:15,533 --> 00:14:16,908
Have we met before?

192
00:14:18,200 --> 00:14:21,033
You seem so... familiar.

193
00:14:22,491 --> 00:14:25,991
I'm embarrassed to say it's been
a while since I visited a library.

194
00:14:26,825 --> 00:14:29,741
[quietly] Well, that's no way
to live, dear.

195
00:14:31,366 --> 00:14:33,116
Let's get you into a good book.

196
00:14:34,033 --> 00:14:34,866
Come.

197
00:14:39,450 --> 00:14:40,783
[keys jangle]

198
00:14:42,075 --> 00:14:43,616
[suspenseful music]

199
00:14:46,325 --> 00:14:47,741
[key turns in lock]

200
00:14:51,575 --> 00:14:52,908
[door creaks]

201
00:15:01,075 --> 00:15:04,158
[music plays quietly
in background]

202
00:15:06,283 --> 00:15:10,616
Anna May, this lovely young lady
wants to open an account with us.

203
00:15:14,325 --> 00:15:15,533
Well,

204
00:15:16,325 --> 00:15:19,616
Madeleine should have told you
that we don't accept new readers

205
00:15:19,700 --> 00:15:21,075
without a reference.

206
00:15:21,616 --> 00:15:23,491
Madeleine had a hunch.

207
00:15:23,575 --> 00:15:26,741
Fudge your hunches,
if you pardon my French.

208
00:15:26,825 --> 00:15:29,575
-Technically not French.
-Always literal.

209
00:15:29,658 --> 00:15:32,991
-Yes, I'm literary. I'm a librarian.
-Be that as it may.

210
00:15:33,075 --> 00:15:34,991
-Florence, dear.
-[music stops]

211
00:15:35,075 --> 00:15:36,408
Would you join us?

212
00:15:36,491 --> 00:15:38,200
[footsteps approach]

213
00:15:38,991 --> 00:15:41,075
I'm afraid
we need a tie-breaker.

214
00:15:41,825 --> 00:15:44,950
Madeleine thinks this girl
needs to do some reading.

215
00:15:45,033 --> 00:15:46,575
I told you I had a hunch.

216
00:15:46,658 --> 00:15:48,491
There's something
very familiar about her.

217
00:15:48,575 --> 00:15:49,908
Hunch, smunch.

218
00:15:49,991 --> 00:15:53,408
I, on the other hand, think
we should dispose of the body

219
00:15:53,491 --> 00:15:57,075
and then have a long talk
about our onboarding protocols.

220
00:15:57,158 --> 00:15:58,700
You know I can hear you, right?

221
00:16:00,408 --> 00:16:01,825
Hush, girl.

222
00:16:02,366 --> 00:16:03,575
Don't be rude.

223
00:16:04,950 --> 00:16:06,241
Turn around, hon.

224
00:16:06,783 --> 00:16:07,908
[annoyed sigh]

225
00:16:16,200 --> 00:16:17,616
And take off your hat.

226
00:16:26,825 --> 00:16:28,700
What did you say your name was?

227
00:16:28,783 --> 00:16:29,866
She didn't.

228
00:16:29,950 --> 00:16:31,575
[Florence] Hmm. That's odd.

229
00:16:32,116 --> 00:16:33,533
[Anna May] Well, girl?

230
00:16:34,491 --> 00:16:36,825
Cat got your tongue? Speak up.

231
00:16:38,658 --> 00:16:39,866
It's Sam.

232
00:16:39,950 --> 00:16:41,700
[soft dramatic music]

233
00:16:41,783 --> 00:16:43,491
Scarlet's kid.

234
00:16:44,200 --> 00:16:45,283
[Sam] Yeah.

235
00:16:45,783 --> 00:16:48,200
I knew it.
Never forget those eyes.

236
00:16:48,283 --> 00:16:51,158
We haven't seen you
since you were yea high.

237
00:16:51,241 --> 00:16:52,616
How is your mother?

238
00:16:53,241 --> 00:16:55,450
[Sam] Haven't seen her
in 15 years.

239
00:16:55,533 --> 00:16:56,491
[Anna May sighs]

240
00:16:57,741 --> 00:17:01,200
Well, that's something
we both have in common.

241
00:17:01,991 --> 00:17:04,741
[Madeleine] My, my, my.
Little Sam.

242
00:17:05,325 --> 00:17:07,908
We hear about you all the time.

243
00:17:07,991 --> 00:17:10,866
You've made
quite a reputation for yourself.

244
00:17:10,950 --> 00:17:13,366
Come here.
Give Auntie Madeleine a hug.

245
00:17:17,575 --> 00:17:18,950
Why come back now?

246
00:17:21,116 --> 00:17:22,241
I needed clean guns...

247
00:17:24,325 --> 00:17:26,241
and I guess I needed an excuse.

248
00:17:27,033 --> 00:17:28,283
[music stops]

249
00:17:29,741 --> 00:17:30,866
[impressed whistle]

250
00:17:30,950 --> 00:17:32,783
Nice collection.

251
00:17:33,533 --> 00:17:35,533
And you take good care of them.

252
00:17:35,616 --> 00:17:38,783
Let me guess.
You're the sentimental type.

253
00:17:39,325 --> 00:17:41,325
Ro-man-tique.

254
00:17:41,408 --> 00:17:43,950
Sentimental types
don't last long doing this.

255
00:17:44,033 --> 00:17:47,908
So, no. I don't think
I'm the sentimental type.

256
00:17:47,991 --> 00:17:49,491
Tommy Tomahawk.

257
00:17:49,991 --> 00:17:51,866
I looked everywhere for him.

258
00:17:51,950 --> 00:17:53,741
Yeah, sorry about that.

259
00:17:54,866 --> 00:17:55,825
So...

260
00:17:57,366 --> 00:17:59,075
you're an idealist.

261
00:17:59,158 --> 00:18:01,783
Nope.
Maybe I don't have a type.

262
00:18:01,866 --> 00:18:03,616
